iVo Loath to Admit Ad Skip Trick
WIRED\xe2\x80\x99s biggest stories delivered to your inbox.
01.14.03
iVo Loath to Admit Ad Skip Trick
01.14.03
iVo Loath to Admit Ad Skip Trick
"that skipping commercials is one of the attractive features of a personal video recorder like TiVo or Sonicblue's ReplayTV."
"Sonicblue heavily promotes a feature in ReplayTV that completely skips over ads at the touch of a button. That's at least one reason a slew of media companies, including AOL Time Warner and Disney, is suing the company."
iVo users can fast-forward through ads on recorded programs. But an undocumented feature \xe2\x80\x93 well-known to the TiVo community \xe2\x80\x93 is a 5-button code that, when activated, makes clicking through a string of ads easier by advancing programming in 30-second intervals with each button click.
he magic combination circulated on weblogs recently and was likely first posted on the 
"While not a new trick, it's one customers like and talk about. Company officials, on the other hand, seem reluctant to discuss it."
"It\'s not an official feature of the service," said Bob Poniatowski, product marketing manager for TiVo. "We don\'t promote it."
Poniatowski said "hackers" figured out the button combination that activates the 30-second skip, which TiVo programmers developed for internal use. "We have more important things to do as a company than stay ahead of these guys," he said.
"It\'s pretty simple," said Aditya Kishore, an analyst with the 
. "They don\'t want to be sued.
"They don\'t want to take on the media establishment," he said.
Marvin Plettner, an unemployed software engineer from Alameda, California, posted on his website 
Plettner emphasized that he did not discover the combination on his own. He posted the directions as a reminder to himself and others.
"I\'d be really disappointed if, for whatever reason, they took away this feature," he said.
"Joe Sacher, a computer consultant and programmer from Indianapolis speculated that in addition to avoiding legal troubles, TiVo doesn't promote the 30-second skip because it would confuse the mainstream consumer."
"They want to keep it simplified for the average user that just wants to bring the unit home, plug it in and use it," Sacher said. "They would get more support calls if they had these functionalities listed in their manual."
acher said he experimented with the 30-second skip but turned it off because he occasionally likes to watch commercials for new movies or television programs. Instead, he has programmed in an add-on feature that automatically sorts recorded shows by program title.
"The Yankee Group's Kishore said it's in TiVo's best interest not to ruffle the feathers of content providers."
He said that when it first launched, the company expected the TiVo units to sell quickly, which has not happened.
"The idea was to make the box as valuable as possible to the consumer and not really worry about the existing television programmers," Kishore said. "As they went on I think they realized that the box was not going to sell as fast as they originally envisioned. That changes the game substantially.
"They don\'t have a whole lot to bargain with, and they need to play nice with the more powerful players."
"They\'re much more in workings with media companies than Replay," Sacher said. "A lot of these business decisions may be driven by not biting the hand that feeds them."
"With or without these secret features, people say they can't live without their TiVos."
"It\'s one of those \'you can pry it from my cold, dead hands\' kind of things," Sacher said.
