"\nThe Bolt will continue to improve. Tivo's always had issues keeping up with all the streaming apps, and possibly will for the foreseeable future, but I think 2016 will be an interesting year."
\nThe latest software release enables the second transcoder for portable devices, so that should cover #4 of the Bad. Transcoding is pretty computationally intense. It\'s "slow" but I respect that it can be done in roughly 2x real-time speed. My 3.3GHz computer isn\'t much faster at it. 
"8) There are (relatively unobtrusive) ads buried throughout the device. When you're paying $150/year in subscription fees, you really don't expect to see ads coming from Tivo itself."
"One of the reasons why I don't want to give up Windows Media Center.  That and having an honest to goodness, full fledged, capable version of Plex (and/or Emby).\n\t\t\t\t\t"
"As to the commercial skip feature, I suspect it's not automatic for the entire show to avoid the legal issues another DVR company faced.  As I understand it, they were slightly different, eliminating the commercials entirely from the recording, but I think requiring user input at each commercial break is probably safer."
o the Dish network DVR has a feature called "AutoHop"
\r\n"To skip commercials during your favorite primetime shows with AutoHop, just wait to view those programs. When AutoHop is enabled, you\'ll be prompted at the first commercial break of your recorded primetime content asking if you\'d like to skip through commercials. Simply indicate "yes," and AutoHop will remember your preference and skip all commercials for the remainder of the program. Freedom from advertisements \xc2\x97 now that\'s something worth waiting for." [
